<section id="database">
    <h2 class="text-2xl mb-3 font-semibold">The Database</h2>
    <p class="my-5">
        Information used by this app is stored in a Heroku PostgreSQL database. On Heroku, it can be found under "Installed add-ons" 
        within the overview tab for this app. Because the free tier of Heroku doesn't provide continuous backup protection and 
        rollback support, it is HIGHLY recommended that you periodically make a manual backup of the database. More information on 
        making and restoring from manual backups can be found 
        <a class="text-blue-600" href="https://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/heroku-postgres-backups" target="_blank">here</a>.
    </p>
</section>

<section id="oauth">
    <h2 class="text-2xl mb-3 font-semibold">Google OAuth</h2>
    <p class="my-5">
        Signing into the SFK Membership Tracker is made easy using Google OAuth. Once signed in, a user will be remembered for two weeks 
        or until they sign out. Google OAuth requires using the Google Cloud Platform, which contains important settings used to configure 
        OAuth for this website. For that reason it is <em>very important</em> that at least one officer has ownership of the project on 
        Google Cloud at all times. The Google Cloud Platform dashboard can be found <a class="text-blue-600" href="https://console.cloud.google.com" target="_blank">here</a>.
    </p>
</section>

<section id="permissions">
    <h2 class="text-2xl mb-3 font-semibold">Member Permissions</h2>
    <p class="my-5">Each membership role within the organization has varying levels of access to the features on this website:</p>
    <ul class="my-5 list-disc">
        <li><b>Applicant</b> - Applicants are capable of checking the status of their application, view announcements, and see upcoming 
        events.</li>
        <li><b>Member</b> - Members have all of the privileges of an applicant, plus the ability to track their participation through 
        the member dashboard and view/edit their information through the profile page.</li>
        <li><b>Officer</b> - Officers have access to the admin dashboard and app documentation (this page). All officers are able to 
        create/edit/delete events and announcements.</li>
        <li><b>Managerial Co-Chair</b> - The Managerial Co-Chair has full control over the website. This includes the ability to 
        edit application questions, approve/reject applicants, edit any member's profile and participation, and edit the About Us and 
        Social Media pages.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="errors">
    <h2 class="text-2xl mb-3 font-semibold">Error Codes</h2>
    <p class="my-5">The following section describes common error codes that a user might encounter when using this app. 
    If you are unsure of what is causing the error, check the logs for this app on Heroku.</p>
    <ul class="my-5 list-disc">
        <li><b>404 - "Not Found"</b>: The page/resource wasn't found. If you're certain that the URL is correct, 
            then the page was most likely moved or deleted.</li>
        <li><b>406 - "Not Acceptable"</b>: This application doesn't support the client's request with a given protocol. 
            A possible solution is to try again using a different browser.</li>
        <li><b>422 - "Unprocessable Entity"</b>: The server understands the type of request being made, but there is an 
            error that is preventing it from being processed. The user will most likely need to diagnose the issue themself.</li>
        <li><b>500 - "Internal Server Error"</b>: The issue is on the server side. It could be caused by anything from 
            unscheduled database maintenance by Heroku to a bug in the code. You will need to check the app logs on Heroku 
            to diagnose the problem.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="github">
    <h2 class="text-2xl mb-3 font-semibold">GitHub</h2>
    <p class="my-5">GitHub is a platform for sharing and collaborating on code. The source code for this app is stored in a 
    private repository (similar to a shared drive) on GitHub. Because this code contains sensitive information such as your API 
    key for Google OAuth, you should <em>never</em> share the repository with anyone who isn't maintaining the website. Likewise, 
    the repository should never be made public. The repo can be found <a class="text-blue-600" href="#" target="_blank">here</a> (Note that visiting 
    this link will give you a 404 error unless you are signed into a GitHub account with access to the repository).</p>
</section>

<section id="transfer">
    <h2 class="text-2xl mb-3 font-semibold">Transferring Ownership</h2>
    <p class="my-5">The following is a checklist of necessary actions to ensure that the next owner has full control of this app:</p>
    <ol class="my-5 list-decimal">
        <li><b>Promote the new owner to Managerial Co-Chair</b>: This can be done by editing their profile in the member roster.</li>
        <li><b>Add them as an owner to the project on Google Cloud Platform</b>: You will see the ability to "add people to this project" 
        under the Project Info pane on the home page of the dashboard. Make sure to give them the role of owner.</li>
        <li><b>Transfer ownership of the Heroku app</b>: </li>
        <li><b>Add them to the GitHub repo</b>: Within the repository, go to settings > manage access to add them as a collaborator.</li>
    </ol>
</section>
